It has the original black center, though you can use green, since for some time it was made with green, but has no actual pin or hole for a pin. This one will last for years.
Please use with respect, in honour of our fallen soldiers.

description.text:
This design was inspired by theorbtwo's marker holder, except I wanted something open that didn't need to be fastened shut.  This part should help rapidly color a length of filament feed stock with a few swipes.
This is designed to take a fine point sharpie marker and paint a 3mm filament.

Print.  The round hole prints horizontally and I was too lazy to put in the teardrop top, so it sags a bit.  It might need some cleaning out, but the three I've printed seemed OK after minimal cleaning.
The plastic tip of the marker should fit snug in the small hole, with about 1mm sticking through.  This should leave a gap on either side of the marking tip, placing filament near the center of the side of the tip.  For full saturation color, you may need to pass over the filament several times, back and front.  (Shifting the filament to the opposite gap makes this easy.)
If your marker or your filament is a different size, you may need to adjust the parameters of the model.  Parameters penbase and pentol control the diameter of the tapered hole for the marker handle, pentip the small hole.  If you use a thinner filament, you may want to increase pentiplen (by 1mm?) so that the entire plastic portion of the tip is inside the block.

This replacement part demonstrates the use of removable pad features to help hold down small part during prints.  The design is as true to the original as I could make it, given my limited skills.  
Enjoy!

The sphericon is a three-dimensional solid with one side and two edges. It was first introduced by the Israeli game and toy inventor David Haran Hirsch who patented it in Israel in 1980. It was given its name by Colin Roberts, of Hertfordshire, England, who also explored it. It may be constructed from a bicone (a double cone) with an apex of 90 degrees, by splitting the bicone along a plane through both apexes, rotating one of the two halves by 90 degrees, and reattaching the two halves. Generalizing this construction to a regular 2n-sided polygon (square, hexagon, octogon ...), will give access to a set of other 3D solids with the same properties as sphericons when rolling on themselves they cover their whole surface. order 2 & 4 are shown in action here: http://youtu.be/8OgA3UW9Adc

the offered parameters you can play with are: sphericon_order : this defines the number of sides of the polygon = 2 * sphericon_order sphericon_diameter : this is the diameter in mm of the sphere in which is included the sphericon full_sphericon : [yes,no] if you want a full sphericon check "yes", but if you prefer to print it in half, check "no" sphericon_angular_offset : if you have checked "yes" for full sphericon, this parameter allows to rotate the two halves by 1 to n sides If you've printed the sphericon in two pieces, a set of cylindrical holes are foreseen to help aligning the two parts. Playing with pin_height and diameter allows either to insert small cylindrical magnets or pieces of plastic filament...

description.text:
Functional Pin Tumble lock. All of the components can be printed with the exception of the helix compression springs. These springs can be taken out of standard click pens. The springs I made this for are 4mm OD and ~20mm long.
I made a small window in the "Outer Barrel" to view the key pin pushing up on the driver pin.
This was a quick project to familiarize myself with the design constraints required for successful FDM designs/prints. I thought I would distribute since it could be fun for teaching and demonstrations.

1)Print all parts
2)Setting the key
a)Insert the key into the plug.
b)Insert 5 key pins into plug.
c)With a pair of wire cutters or knife, cut the key pins to be flush with the surface of the plug. Sand as necessary.
d) Remove key and press all key pins back into the plug.
3)Inserting plug
a)Cut remaining key pin short (~5mm or so).
b)Insert spring then short key pin into the side of the plug
c)While compressing the spring, insert plug into outer barrel.
d)Rotate into position to align key pins with holes for driver pins.
e)Add retaining ring at end of plug to capture the plug.
4)Inserting driver pins
a)Insert driver pins into 5 available holes. (The smaller OD goes on top and will help capture the spring)
b)Insert springs into 5 available holes.
c)Compress the back spring to be flush with the surface of the outer barrel.
d)Slide the top over the first spring and compress the next.
e)Continue until all springs are covered and top secured.
5)Play

This adapter is for Robo3D R1 Plus 3D printer. I use this adapter to replace the stock 25mm extruder fan with a very quiet fan. I tried several 25mm fan and found most of them poorly made. So I design this adapter so that it will fit 40mm fan. After replacing the fan, the temperature is stable. Use the original screws to mount the adapter to the original screw holes. I use 15mm flat head screw and cap to mount the 40mm fan (the bottom two holes) and about 12mm wood screw to secure the top two holes. Important YOU MUST ALSO REPLACE THE SCREW THAT SET THE X-MIN. IT NEEDS TO BE 10mm LONGER. This is important because the head is now thicker by 10mm on the left side. Print the design upside down. Otherwise, the bottom won't stick. And print with support structure. I also did two things to finally reduce the fan noise to acceptable level - replace the power supply and bottom plate fan. In case you are wondering how to reduce the total fan noise.

This is a preliminary design of a cheap, lightweight FPV backpack. I wanted a system that was able to be carried by a variety of RC aircraft including my FT mini Scout and was also easy to assemble. Right now, this weighs in at 22g. It will simply be attached via a couple of slots on the airplane and a velcro "cable keeper" strap. I may add another piece of velcro under the case for a little more security, but I doubt it's necessary. The camera, which is attached via a piece of double-stick foam tape, is powered off the VTX and the whole thing can be powered from the main flight battery or an independent 2S, 3S, 4S, 5S, or 6S lipo battery. The transmitter takes in anywhere from 7V to 24V and puts out a clean 5V to the camera. All of the parts can be purchased through Amazon which makes things easy. I may eventually add a different camera mount that allows the angle to be adjusted. This would open up some additional mounting options and would be very useful on multirotors. Transmitter used:

http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00IEXTOMA?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00 Cheap Circular Polarized Antenna:
http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00LGM2U0E?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00

• Determine how much cable you need to connect the camera to the VTX. If you're going to solder the connections directly, you'll want to do this before you put it in the case.

  • Mount the VTX into the case. Foam tape, hot glue, or just friction fit should work fine. The velcro strap will keep the VTX in the case if you want to keep it easily removable.

  • Mount the camera to the case using foam tape, hot glue, etc.

  • Strap to something RC and enjoy!

title: Gopro Tripod Mount with Nut Insert

description.text:
This is a Gopro tripod mount I made for a monopod. I tried to download one from thingiverse but no one had a good design with a nut insert that would keep it locked tight to the pod. Just go to your local hardware store and get a 1/4 nut and put it in the open slot with some super glue and your good to go! Use a nail file or similar to file the excess inside the hole to make the nut fit snug, also between the wedges to make a tight fit and not stretch the print apart. It will snap if you do trust me I've redesigned this model about 4 times before uploading this one. Price on the nut is cheaper that a bag of rocks.
Here you are guys hope this help anyone in the same situation out as me. Enjoy!
P.S. I tweaked the first version of the uploaded file to make some of the gaps tighter, please feel free to download the latest version.

Big shoutout to the boys over at SNW for advice on this one. :) Okay boys, this is the one that is relatively easy to print, but extremely difficult to print right. It's best to just CNC this one. Xplorer has kept this breech design behind their "woohoo ironcurtain ironcurtain ironcurtain" for just too long, so I have reverse engineered it and reworked the concept. The idea is that the bolt and breech not only mate very well, but the conic frustum (look it up son) guides the dart very smoothly into the breech. An ingenious concept, Xplorer was probably not the first to do this, but the first to apply it to Nerf and prove that it works better. But, all empires will fall in time. For shame! Edit:
Design overthrown. Xplorer is now hardly even related to this design. (first of all, they wouldn't make a dart tooth that weak if it meant saving their virginity, but luckily it hasn't come to that) Now uses a soft O-ring. It makes me happier. :)

IDEATION FOR THIS DESIGN BEGAN WITH A MIND MAP WHERE I LET MY MIND FREE TO BOUNCE FROM IDEA TO IDEA. 
THE MAIN IDEAS I FOUND I COULD POSSIBLY DEVELOP INTO AN ENJOYABLE AND EDUCATIONAL TOY WERE PULLEYS AND MOTION.
I BEGAN TO CONCEIVE POSSIBLE WAYS I COULD INCORPORATE THESE IDEAS INTO A 3D PRINTABLE TOY CAR.
TRADITIONAL PULL BACK CARS WERE A JOY TO ME AS A CHILD SO I DECIDED TO MAKE ONE THAT USED PULLEYS AND TENSION FOR PROPULSION.

SOME SHAVING OF THE SLIDE BARS IS NECESSARY IN ORDER TO MAKE THEM SLIDE ADEQUATELY.
LOW FRICTION LINE IS NECESSARY, I RECOMMEND FISHING LINE. THIS IS TO BE STRUNG THROUGH THE HOLES AND TIED OFF TO THE SMALLEST PART IN THE PRINT (VIEW PHOTO TITLED MECHANICS AND OPERATION FOR HELP SETTING UP THIS PULLEY ARRANGEMENT). 
DUE TO THE SIZE RESTRAINT, IT IS NECESSARY TO USE A DROP OF SUPER GLUE TO BETTER BIND THE SLIDE BARS AFTER THEY ARE SNAPPED TOGETHER.
SHARPENING TWO NEW PENCILS ON BOTH ENDS CREATES THE AXLES AND THE WHEEL CAPS ARE SQUEEZED ONTO THE ENDS OF THE PENCILS AFTER THEY ARE IN PLACE WITH THE WHEELS ON THE CARS CHASSIS. THEN DROPS OF SUPER CLUE IN EACH WHEEL HOLE FURTHER BIND THE WHEELS TO THE PENCIL AXLES TO GIVE THE CAR ITS PULL BACK CAPABILITIES.
PUSH PINS NEED TO BE PUSHED INTO THE PENCILS WHERE THE PRINTED LINE ENDS PROTRUDE FROM THE REAR OF THE CAR.

This little creation is a a solution to my every day problems.
I thought others may benefit from the design.
*Update - added Version 2 as well. Video:
https://youtu.be/T69_0_q7X-g
  • Version 1 can hold the following:
    • Up to 6 credit cards (without notes)
    Up to 5 Credit cards (with a note or two)
    3 X $2 coins (Australian) (with aux storage in use)
    9 X $2 coins (Australian) (with aux storage occupied by coins)
    4 X micro SD cards
    1 X standard SD card
    1 X floss/toothpick
    1 X Loc8tor radio locator tag
    *Aux storage compartment for small items (EG: card reader)

  • Version 2 (recently added):
    Adds a space for a Verbatim Store and go, Nano USB stick.
    The Aux storage area has also been expanded to accommodate more stuff like WiFi adapters, compact OTG adapters and small card readers.
    The radio tracker used in this project can be purchased from http://www.loc8tor.com/
    they work very well, and are quite accurate.

  • Version 3 - coming later tonight!
    • If printed in transparent ABS, this design will allow you to see the flashing LED through the case. If you would like a variant/remix - I can supply source files, or redesign it for you.
    My time, however, is limited so it may take time.
